    "name": "COU1: Cardiopulmonary bypass use (Class II)",
    "type": "ContextOfUse"
  },
  "hasValidationResult": [
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/no-comparator",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Primary hemolysis index validation — comparator link absent",
      "description": "CFD-predicted relative hemolysis index (RH) values were computed across all five flow-speed operating points defined in the COU. The simulation results were assessed against in-vitro hemolysis measurements reported by Morrison et al. (2022) for the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump operated under pulsatile CPB-representative conditions. Agreement was characterised by normalised RMS error of 8.3% across the five operating points, with all predicted RH values falling below the acceptance threshold of 1.0. The Morrison et al. (2022) dataset is referenced in the narrative, but no formal comparedAgainst link to that dataset object is recorded in this result record. The absence of a machine-readable comparator link means downstream automated credibility audits cannot confirm that the cited dataset is appropriate for the declared COU, leaving the comparator identity unverifiable without manual inspection of the narrative text."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/steady-state-comparator",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Secondary velocity-field validation — steady-state PIV comparator (COU mismatch)",
      "description": "A second validation activity compared CFD-predicted velocity fields inside the pump volute against particle image velocimetry (PIV) measurements drawn from the FDA GCBP steady-state benchmark dataset (acquired at constant impeller speed, constant flow rate, no pulsatility). Mean velocity magnitude agreement was within 6% at all measurement planes. However, the declared COU specifies pulsatile flow conditions representative of cardiopulmonary bypass, where instantaneous flow rates vary by ±35% of the mean over each cardiac cycle. The steady-state PIV comparator cannot represent the unsteady flow structures — particularly the periodic recirculation zones near the impeller blade tips — that drive peak shear stress and therefore peak hemolysis under pulsatile conditions. Using a steady-state experimental reference to validate a model deployed under pulsatile COU conditions constitutes an inference-method mismatch: the comparator is technically present and well-documented, but its experimental regime is fundamentally inconsistent with the conditions under which the model will be used. This mismatch is noted here but was not treated as disqualifying during the assessment, which constitutes the W-AR-05 / D3 weakness.",
      "comparedAgainst": "https://uofa.net/synth/data/fda-gcbp-piv-steady-2021"
    }
  ],
